<br>
In terms of the objectives Bush set out almost a year ago, the war on terrorism is largely a failure.  Al-Quada is not broken, and as far as we know its head is in place and unfindable.  So what's a president to do?<br>
<br>
You turn to the next most hated enemy, Saddam Hussein, and kick him around a little.  It's something like an abusive husband who kicks the dog when his wife leaves him.  At least, that's what it looks like to me.<br>
<br>
Iraq has not said they're harboring Al-Quada or bin Laden.  They claim they're not making weapons of mass destruction.  They deny the charges the U.S. is making.  Are they reliable?  No.  However, all we have are our assumptions.  We don't have a link between bin Laden and Hussein, beyond that they're both Middle Eastern, both dislike the U.S., and they were both once U.S.-sponsored agents (under Reagan, by the way).<br>
<br>
However, Hussein's an easier target than bin Laden because he's the head of state, and maybe a regime change (read: killing him) will satiate the American's desire for vengeance.  Basically, attacking Iraq is really about playing a shell game with the American public.<br>
<br>
Furthermore, it won't actually resolve anything.  The Iraqi public dislikes America intensely after the Persian Gulf War.  Ousting Hussein won't improve those relations, and we'll just wind up with yet another group of disaffected persons from whom Al-Quada could recruit. <p>"These discourses of heterosexuality oppress us in the sense that they prevent us from speaking unless we speak in their terms."<BR>
